caption: I had the special St Valentine's Afternoon Tea service and enjoyed it very much. It's a great combination of environment, ambience and quality of food and tea. I like their non traditional interpretation on afternoon tea and that there was a nice balance between savory & sweet bites. More often than not afternoon teas tend to lean more towards sweet bites. I think because it was holiday special it was $65/pp included nicer items such as oysters, beef tartare, roe and (verse simple stuff like cucumber sandwiches and mini quiches etc.) and included a glass of Prosecco. The cost was pricey and I wish it include a few more bites (there was 12 total, with no repeats) but I'd say cost to value it's on par (if not a little higher) with other DC hotels Afternoon Tea service that includes a glass of alcohol.  Bites included (from memory): - Two oysters - Beef tartare with salmon roe (my favorite) - Asian pear Camembert cheese and honey - Smoked salmon with whipped herbed cheese - pappadam crisp (my favorite) - a smoke fish salad on crisp - mini chocolate caramel tarte - olive oil & something cake -sugar coated grapes - cheese filled date with honey (not pictured) - French macron - coco flan type dessert. This was out of place being usually large and dense (I took it to go).
Chicken sandwich was not up to snuff

I'm giving 1 star for poor business practices. On Dec 19, I made a reservation for Dec 27th. I showed up at my reservation time, and the staff said that they were shut down for in-person dining, both indoor and outdoor. They did not notify me in advance that my reservation was canceled even though my reservation was confirmed in Resy. The restaurant did not take any responsibility for this problem and was more defensive than anything. If you want to patronize a restaurant that is a true business, pick a place like Tiger Fork instead of this place. We made a reservation at Tiger Fork once, and they had to cancel our reservation due to inclement weather, but they called us to let us know and to reschedule. That is what a real restaurant does: respects their customers. Please go somewhere else, not here.

Not a huge deal but kind of a scam to say they’d only charge us if we wanted them to cut it for us, then actively block us from doing what they had said we could do. $30 for cutting a $90 cake is really dodgy. This being a trendy hotel restaurant — the lobby of the Line hotel in Adams Morgan, flanked by two bars — there’s cavatelli with ragu made with minced vegetables and a burger with an egg and pork belly on it. Erik Bruner-Yang’s all-day menu seems to check all the current boxes, from “toast” to tuna, as in crudo jolted with ginger in a splash of coconut milk. Asian touches abound; yuzu aioli is a better dunk than ketchup for fries. But the main reason to drop by is Pichet Ong. The former architect is the pastry chef, and I’ve never had anything less than dreamy from him. Ong draws inspiration from Chinese pantry staples — ginger, tea, rice — and favorite childhood sweets. He says he was thinking of Maltesers candies when he created his “Brooklyn” cake: a dome shaped with devil’s food swollen with espresso, banana pudding, salted caramel and vanilla cream. His desserts, including a matcha cake with berry mousse, are blessedly restrained in their sweetness. Ice creams are presented on chewy rice flour wafers: Go for pistachio, veined with crushed candied nuts. You may wait (and wait) to be seated and wait (and wait) for a drink to find its way to you. But you’ll never be disappointed to order “just dessert, please.”

Each piece of the puzzle was great, but the real stand out was the setting. Located within the LINE Hotel which sits within a re-imagined historic church building, Brothers and Sisters shares the great hall of this architectural masterpiece with two other restaurants, two bars and the hotel lobby. It is beautiful and full of life.  The service was friendly and competent. We ordered a bottle of French rose, which really hit the spot with dinner. The duck consomme was spicy, delicious and just what a cold winter night calls for. The brussel sprouts were cooked perfectly and accessorized with caramelized and fried onions which and a sauce which took them to another level. The burger was quite good but the fries were a masterpiece. Finally, they provided us a piece of amazing Earl Grey cake on the house which was a very pleasant surprise. We highly recommend.

The Line Hotel has three restaurants inside to cater to everyone's tastes, and I'm slowly making my way through the list. However, the first spot was undeniably Brothers and Sisters. I was drawn by the concept and its visionary creator, Erik Bruner-Yang who runs Maketto. Not to mention, the genius behind the drinks of Brothers and Sisters is Todd Thrasher, who is my favorite mixologist in the area (known for PX, Restaurant Eve, and the soon-to-be-open Potomac Distilling Company at the Wharf).  The lobby of the hotel, flanked by twin bars on either side, is actually the dining room of Brothers and Sisters. If you sit in the open lounge, you can look upward to a fancy, spiky chandelier fashioned from church organ pipes, paying homage to the hotel's former life as a historic church. We sat at one of the bars and ordered some drinks to start.  I opted for "I Used to be Named Sherlock Holmes but I have Matured," which is Suntory Toki whisky, lapsung souchang syrup, lemon peel, and lemon oil. My other half chose the "It's You and Me and We are Back Again." This one is Belle Mead whiskey with umeshu and topped with satsuma soda. Both cocktails were phenomenal, very Todd Thrasher-like. If you don't like the sound of these contemporary drinks, they do offer classic cocktails too. However, I would recommend any of the quirky, unique cocktails that they've whipped up.  Food-wise, we ordered the uni tray service, knife cut noodles, and the beef short rib burger. The uni tray - though expensive - is delicious. And playful! Here, the uni is served upon some ice and comes with an assortment of toppings like chives, cheese, onions, salt, etc. The knife cut noodles were also fantastic. The chewiness of the noodles paired well with the crunchiness of the fennel sausages and greens (gai lan and asparagus). And of course, the beef short rib burger. Simple, straightforward, lovely. Loved that it was topped with toasted Hawaiian rolls instead of the traditional bun. Also, the side of fries that comes with the burger are sprinkled with nori (insert mind blown gif).  The menu is true Erik Bruner-Yang - eclectic flavors that work collaboratively and fuse multiple cultures together in one. I love it. I recommend it to all.

Ate there recently Drinks were creative, well made and impressive.  The food was also solid, nice flavors, well prepared.  The menu feels a bit hard to approach but every item held up well.  Where they really felt down is service.   water not refilled, plates left all over the table, drinks for my daughter not refilled without us asking.  Then check brought without asking about coffee or another beverage.  A customer shouldn’t feel a lack of hospitality, rushed out or unwelcome and while the drinks and the food stand well, the setting is right up our alley and the drinks were challenging and delivered, peole remember how you make them feel and we felt that we weren’t taken care of.   There is too much good food available to waste a dining experience somewhere that forgets we are in the hospitality business.

However, the French fries and hush puppies were to die for. They were the best part. Overall, a relaxed atmosphere with special drinks, good apps, and a beautiful interior.

The manager came over with the potato pancake which was again way too salty for me. We got the bill which included the entire breakfast. At this point, the tip was getting smaller and smaller. The manager came over after the bill was run through to give me a discount but was also trying to explain why the 2nd pancake was no better than the first. No apologies and the service was poor. I did get a discount off of breakfast after the mgr came by - however the server should have conversed with the mgr prior to giving me the bill for the entire amount. Won't be going there again.

Avocado salad was uniquely presented and had novel spices and was refreshing. Tuna crudo had a kick but was very tasty! Chicharrones- airy , spicy with French onion dip. Yum. Octopus hot dog was ok but chewy. Potato Rosti- hash browns meets spices - great! Cheesecake was amazing!
Great cocktails! The space is gorgeous. Highly recommend for any occasion, be it with friends, on a date, or by yourself. New favorite spot.

I feel like this could have been better.  Sat at the bar, and asked if the octopus hotdog had any dairy.  Instead of telling me that it did and asking if there was something else to order, I was delivered a dry tentacle with no bread, or dressing.  They didn't fix it or comp anything.  Water was only refilled once in an hour.
What a gorgeous space - delicious food, too - all in our neighborhood! We will definitely be back...
